Social media is it's very own thing. If your organization has made some unintentional gaff and is getting flack for it online, it is probably not a good idea to try and tell those you have upset that they are wrong.

@jmschreiber91 Just one note. CTCF is a complete outlier TF since its binding is essentially very stable across cell types (not true for most other factors). So average predictor wud pretty much be as good as it gets. This is not true for almost any other TF. 1/

The second issue is that if you use cell type invariant features, like nucleotide sequence, a complex model may end up simply memorizing this average activity if your model isn't already beating it (b/e above). That's another reason to always compare!

This means that, without a a good understanding of demography, it's difficult to look at patterns of diversity and make clear inference about changes in the efficacy of natural selection (which many of us are guilty of!)

But what's this mean for real samples? Look at the bottom left panels of the figure. Depending on when you sampled, you could find ratios of œÄ/œÄ0 higher or lower than expectations, and ratios of Œæ/Œæ0 (density of singleton variants) that had similar or opposite patterns.

In the botteneck example, what's happening is that sites undergoing linked selection are actually more affected by a bottleneck, as a larger % of variants  are at low frequency. Eventually the decreased efficacy of selection takes over,  and you get hit equilibrium expectations.

But instead we see that this ratio DECREASES directly after a bottleneck. The same is true for expansion -- classic models predict œÄ/œÄ0 should decrease (because selection is more effective in a bigger pop) but it INCREASES instead. What the heck?

For example, when Ne decreases because of a bottleneck, classical models (dotted line) predict that the ratio of œÄ (diversity at linked sites) / œÄ0 (diversity at sites unaffected by linked selection) should increase, as natural selection becomes less effective https://t.co/OHjmejBifd

Here is a quote from the paper: stem cells might primarily use apoptotic pathway to eliminate cells containing massively damaged DNA, whereas postmitotic differentiated cells, which have lost self-renewal capacity, mainly employ nucleotide excision repair to cope with DNA damage
Cells become more UV-resistant with differentiation.
Most repair factors (XPA, XPC, XPG, and XPFERCC1) are upregulated with differentiation.
The capacity increase increase is not associated with apoptotic signal in the stem cells.
Once cells are differentiated, their nucleotide capacity increases.

When you have a one-way ticket and cannot go back, you would know the value of what you have and try to protect them as much as possible. So do your cells! This is a differentiation story of cells in terms of repair capacity. See the flow.

Have a read if you're a biologist & you'd like to contemplate ethics more than the bare minimum, or if you're not & want to learn about some of the really scary shit we may face in the future if we don't properly address the ethical conundrums of the present.

Anyway, I'm new to bioethics and neuroethics (and yes, I'm disturbed at my own ignorance to these fields!). I just read this 2014 perspective from @rose_nikolas and found it to be particularly thought-provoking.https://t.co/Q4y8dmLSVK

We need to be incorporating ethical analyses into our research from the beginning, when we're formulating hypotheses & designing experiments. Ethics should not be an afterthought, something we briefly consider as we revise & submit the same old documents for IRB & IACUC approval.

I can't really tell you what I learned from those trainings aside from very basic concepts like give authorship credit where it's due, don't sleep w/ your advisor, & definitely don't make CRISPR babies. Ethics needs to be a much larger part of STEM training than it currently is.

Despite having been a biology researcher for 7+ years, my ethics training is almost nonexistent. My pre-doc training grant required 1 hour of ethics training, which we completed during lunch at our annual retreat. And my grad program required a one-time, 2 credit ethics course.

- check in, if you still aren‚Äôt feeling better. Or are constantly feeling something; seek your therapist research for therapy. You have the power and magic to break the cycle, and can and will grow.
- remember all the places you get love from, and remember all the places you give love too

- pretend you are yourself a year ago, and think of the dialogue produced when looking at your current self, and how far you‚Äôve come, what new things you‚Äôve learned, what milestones you‚Äôve reached.
- do this as many times as you need to.

- really take a few quiet minutes to affirm to yourself that not all bad moments, spaces, feelings are permanent and invite whatever you are feeling to meet you. Pinpoint its source and greet it, listen to it and then let it leave and listen to your body relax as it does.

- get up, wash your face or a small activity that you know is easy to finish up (e.g make your bed, feed your pet, make a cup of coffee). My morning skincare routine subliminally tells me it‚Äôs time to get the day rolling, so I follow through with the momentum.

For @kph3k op-Ed  I think casting genetics as a ‚Äúluck‚Äù is ...a  reasonable position. Society then has decide how much luck is ‚Äúevened out‚Äù by ... society, state, local or federal. This goes to long-standing discussions - equality of outcome vs equality of opportunity

This seems like good evidence that environmental changes are (at least somewhat) effective here. It feels to me that this rather obvious but nevertheless valid observation is ... worth trying to work what *is* different between these environments of obesity generation

I am also somewhat surprised that people aren‚Äôt commenting more on the French or Danish or Swedish obesity trend (not UK as trends closer to US). FR/DK/SE genetics is very close to US/UK genetics but the obesity trend is flattening

All that said and done, on @skathire genetics of obesity - I find this less surprising than responses seem to make it; we‚Äôve known this for a while, and the (soft) predictability of obesity feels less useful that CAD or Breast cancer where there is public health interventions now
(A note; be aware that language has broader interpretations with this broader audience and far more questions about motivation and underlying positions get asked in policy and politics)
It does however mean that in these science meets policy +  politics  crosses US/ UK / Canadian / Australian policy+politics with participanting scientists worldwide. It makes for a powerful mixture

The next thing to realise is that policy and politics is national ; science is international. In English speaking countries we‚Äôre lucky that the international language of science is the same as our national language
Furthermore it‚Äôs harder to take a neutral point of view (or know where that precisely is) - here a diversity of views is key (ideally with the science twitter mindset - polite, curious)

We‚Äôre likely to get more of these over time so we should get used to this. Stepping back genetics (and science in general) is often very indifferent to broad politics, supporting or refuting things that come from left or right

Both of these are examples of genetics moving away from fundamental biology into human behaviour, with a far closer relationship to policy and even politics. This broadens audiences and creates more potential for angst
Both of them are dealing with some twitter criticism with aplomb and should be applauded for responding both curious questions and sometimes impolite critiques

10./ regional jets (particularly the CRJ-700) are way more succeptible to turbulance than bigger jets and it can be scary if you don't like sudden drops.

9./ QC metrics on ENCODE portal are good, but they aren't perfect. There is some good data there that is flagged. If you aren't sure, reach out to the production team. They are usually v nice and love talking about their work.

8./ Another important note: while the @ENCODE_DCC does a great job including info on genetic perturbations, treatments, etc. of biosamples, those aren't included in the "biosample" data field. Use "biosample summary" to filter!!

7./ Comparison across biological replicates is extremely important for filtering out questionable peaks. In the words of one scientist there, "you have replicates, use them." This can mean using IDR-thresholded peaks rather than replicate-specific ones.

6./ ChIP-seq assays are "semi-quantitative" at best. Exact p-values / fold change / read-counts shouldn't be trusted as much as a coarse view (like peak calls). For example, a -log10 p-value of 60 is not really that different from 80, but 5 is very different from 25.
5./ Don't be afraid of the GFP or FLAG tagged data on the ENCODE portal! I originally thought that it would be lower quality, but it is not.

4./ Older TF assays use a different antibody for each TF, making signal across experiments difficult to compare. Newer TF assays genetically modify the TF gene to include a tag (FLAG or GFP) and use a single antibody to grab that, significantly increasing signal-to-noise
3./ This means that if you see a peak in TF ChIP-seq, it likely means that the TF is nearby and potentially influencing activity, but it doesn't mean that TF is directly binding to the sequence there

2./ Histone mod ChIP-seq is generally good at directly measuring the modification. However, TF ChIP-seq can be confounded by indirect effects, e.g., TF "A" might bind to TF "B" and "B" binds to DNA, but assaying "A" shows a peak

AMF ultimately closed and moved south (broken up, I think?). For me it was the start of watching stable jobs leave and nobody able to find something that kept them employed for more than ~10 years. The decline of the rust belt is another story, but guys like this had a big role.

One memory comes to mind from 1987. I had a little league game, but there was a tornado and the game ended early. We arrived home and broke up a robbery. My dad was a part of union leadership and they managed to steal some union documents from our house. Interesting times.

After taking over the company, he started slashing costs and forced successive 25% pay cuts on the employees. This led to a lot of bad times in my household as a kid. My mom started working a night shift at a gas station and the union eventually went on strike at AMF.

As the "kmer length" gets larger, eventually most possible kmers are found at 0 or 1 times. For the largest kmers, I could thus use a single bit to keep track of their counts.

"counter-len" defines how many bits are used for each count entry in the hash. If too small, the program uses multiple hash entries to maintain the total count... slowing things down dramatically. Once the bit size is large enough, no count bin is overwhelmed, so no big slowdown.

We tested this using categoryCompare v2, which is able to work with the output of GOCats mappings, and now has a command line API, which was partly done so that it would be easier for @ehinderer to do the actual evaluation for this manuscript.#moseleybioinfo /7

A side effect of grouping GO terms using GOCats, is an increase in statistical power. In that, with fewer things to test, it seems we are more likely to see relevant grouped terms after multiple testing correction.https://t.co/eE30dRfqND#moseleybioinfo /6

Namely, you could end up with some groupings that make absolutely no sense from a hierarchical point of view. Working around this required a re-interpretation of some of the relationships, and some cool lexical work.#moseleybioinfo /5

In the process of trying to aggregate GO terms using the graph structure, @ehinderer discovered that some very nasty things happened if you just assumed you could follow relationships in particular directions.#moseleybioinfo /4

For information, GO is one source of gene product annotations, that I'm particularly interested in using to summarize high-throughput -omics data. It is a controlled vocabulary, organized as a graph.#moseleybioinfo /3

Anyone who has worked with Gene Ontology (GO) enrichment knows that there is a lot of redundancy. There are some solutions to this (one I borrowed for categoryCompare), but none of them are *really good*, and few are good and automatics#moseleybioinfo /2

Paper 3: Work with @ehinderer, who is writing his dissertation as we speak, and will be in the Boston area as of this summer.https://t.co/ZyrCMen9iUEugene has been interested in how we can automatically group Gene Ontology annotations#moseleybioinfo /1

As a PostDoc, Sen is right now working on software related to differences in the crystallographic model, and the underlying electron density. She is also looking for a job in data science, and is a really good #python developer!#moseleybioinfo /11
We first did this work for proteins that have Zn, and then extended it to the 5 most abundant metals.#moseleybioinfo /10

Turns out the different coordination geometries are specific to different functions. The "aberrant" ones have very crooked angles, or even missing ligands, and seemed to be enriched for enzymatic proteins.#moseleybioinfo /9

I was also involved in helping to see if there were unique biological functions that were enriched in the proteins that had belonged to different coordination geometries, using categoryCompare (see previous thread).#moseleybioinfo /8

I was involved in writing code that detected duplicate sequences of peptides around the metal binding site, as we didn't want to inflate numbers by looking at the same thing multiple times.#moseleybioinfo /7

So Sen came up with some metrics to discard truly "out there" structures, and we were able to detect and characterize some previously un-described coordination geometries from protein structures in the protein data bank.#moseleybioinfo /6

If you throw out these weird coordination geometries, then everything is fine (others took this approach). However, their numbers in the crystallographic record imply that they are not simply artifacts of how the protein crystals are grown.#moseleybioinfo /5

The initial implementation of this did really weird, unexpected things. It turns out that these unexpected things were actually the result of very odd coordination geometries that didn't fit "canonical" models#moseleybioinfo /4

Background: lab was interested in detecting and clustering metal coordination sites automatically using statistical properties. Metals are important for biological function, and the way metal is bound can influence function, as form dictates function#moseleybioinfo /3
I ended up working with Sen on these because I overheard her and PI having issues, and suggested visualizing data to try and determine what was going on.#moseleybioinfo /2

So - genetics is not the definitive description of what is going on causally. Many other things - random chance, decisions, where and how you grow up  - have as strong if not stronger influence. Genetics - and GWAS - is just a really useful starting point for many human traits.

This is miscommunication - every trait is mixture of genetics and "other things" (lumped together as "environment" - not a great term); us finding *some* of the variance in the population is due to genetics absolutely does *not* mean *all* of it is. Indeed, quite the opposite

Finally I know the enthusiasm that someone us talk about genetics (*cough* myself included) can come over as overbearing - people can misread geneticists as thinking that *everything* is genetics because of the genome-wide nature of genetics.

Some of this loss of precision is choice (genotyping rather than sequencing) but a large chunk is just inherent in human data - LD is too strong, haplotypes "too long, too common" to get precision. Take home - the "top SNP" is no guarantee that *this SNP* is causal.

We can use this correlation to not to have to test every variant to find regions which are specifically associated (genotyping arrays cutting down on markers - v. useful 10 years ago, still useful now in terms of price) but... we lose precision of which precise variant

It is also correlated because the human population exploded so rapidly out of Africa we are still dominated by the "founder population" of those humans some ~100,000 years ago - very much we are still "one tribe" of 7 billion odd people in terms of our genetics. Weird but true.

Some people pointed out I didn't go into LD complications in fine mapping either - this is true, it was something I didn't dive into. To set the scene - variation in the human genome is correlated due to the fact that recombination along chromosomes is both rare and bursty

But people can get jumpy about this because they think that people talking about genetics of behaviour are implying genetic determinism - more on this below, but this absolutely *not* the case; all human geneticists are in a Nature and Nurture mode (both together).

Again, other people have broader and longer expositions of this (in particular @mendel_random, grandfather of the field) but one can trace "causality" (again, this slippery word) between different exposures and behaviours in humans

One very fruitful approach is not to use genetics as "strong" predictors, but to leverage the random nature of genetics (given you have handled population structure; see above!) of many, often weak, effects in Mendelian randomisation
This "genetics impacts behaviour which impacts something else" is somewhat similar to the "extended phenotype" of Dawkin and opens up big parts of human behaviour to a novel approach using genetics

(Two of my favourite researchers in this space is @AmelieBaud who has been bringing this thinking into mammals - mice and rats - and humans, and @AlexTISYoung who has been looking at this in human family structure)

Some commentators do not like how the "causal pathway" of some genetics goes through very complex routes, such as behaviour. This is ... more ok than you think IMO. Again, as many things in genetics, animal breeders have been looking at this for *decades* (Social Genetic Effects)

Once we're confident on this, the step above this - a system level view - will likely be deployed in very careful over-data sampled world (insane mapping of roads; high instrumentation in ICU; specific image acquisition domains). A sort of constrained universe.

FM on principles of federated learning, Share models (improve locally, send back, share again, repeat at different institutes) need not share data, while model quality increases. Links to federated analysis initiatives like the #personalhealthtrain in @ELIXIRNL @maqcsociety

Obviously, what you changes you track in a package or shiny app is different to a local analysis repo. Using #git (as a researcher) only for developing software and sharing on @github is losing a lot of potential.

Still plenty I can do to improve my workflow but it‚Äôs evolved recently and I couldn‚Äôt have done it without experience using (and teaching) git. Once a repo is set up tracking and updating metadata as you go is hassle-free. Also great to have backups that you can import anywhere.

Comments on their own often aren‚Äôt enough to understand the project later on. A git repo on its own is not enough. With plain text documenting the purpose and changes made it‚Äôs great for lab notes. It‚Äôs timestamped so you‚Äôre covered for IP or precedence issues if they crop up.

This practice is fundamentally missing the power of version control in scientific analysis. Keeping track of code, output, figures, and plain text readmes/changelogs for tracking changes together makes fixing or redoing things way easier.cc: @gvwilson @JennyBryan https://t.co/bYeMXTfjVG

That‚Äôs not a criticism. It‚Äôs the entire point of working in a team with diverse backgrounds (yes that includes countries, cultures, and upbringing). As an interdisciplinary researcher, I‚Äôll willingly admit I have weaker in stats, molecular bio, and CS than if I‚Äôd focused on one.

These research internships exist (and are great) but they‚Äôre no replacement for the expertise of researchers. It is simply impossible to gain technical proficiency in that short a time or offer it to all MDs. Intern projects are carefully designed and optimised before they start.

We‚Äôve worked with many med and science student interns. Most have been fantastic and thrived in a research environment. Still it was clear they hadn‚Äôt done it before. Even MD-PhDs have limits to their knowledge from broader undergrad training. They have insights we don‚Äôt too.

Most researchers are aware of this. We don‚Äôt find holes on our expertise in other fields a critique of our character. I think this is because we often work with scientists in other fields. We struggle to use or understand their techniques as well. We need each other.

The reaction from clinicians to this is deeply concerning. You don‚Äôt have as much experience as someone doing it their entire career. This should be obvious not controversial. Do I think this is terminal? Is the UK going to permanently lose its tolerance, welcome + good sense? With good leadership + the many sane people in this country no. But we are poorly served by our current leaders, so it is serious. One of the many things to fix due to Brexit

For the politicians who enable this- and make no mistake you do- this is the toxic side effect of a process you started, you let grow out of control, + you thought was perhaps high minded politics or your own career. This affects many people, and you are collectively responsible

So - as a Brit - I deeply apologise for this. I will object whenever I see this; I will fight for every person who comes to this country + contributes; my Britain is tolerant, curious, confident of our culture to absorb parts of many others (from bon mots to chicken tikka to tea)

And by British - to be clear - this usually means "speaks with some type of British / English accent, with white skin". It's not simply ugly+ impolite; it is immoral, stupid and plain wrong. Many "straight" Brits don't fit this architype, let alone the numerous foreign residents

She walked on without comment (there were children around; don't make a scene), but it eats at me. Brexit has not simply drawn back a curtain on small minded thinking, but it's narrative actively encourages people to think such crude nativism is somehow right

She is an amazing woman - has contributed to the UK both materially (taxes), intellectually (she is one of the best scientists I know) + plays a full part in her local (Islington) and professional (scientific) British culture. Of course Britain should be her home.

Her first thought "I didn't take your job, I was the best person" ; her second "I pay my taxes" ; her third "I am an Italian, married to an American / British dual citizen, my daughter has British passport and is growing up in London - where is my home?"
The most soul eating point though was when one colleague described being shouted at to "go back home" (she was walking in whitstable kent, with her young daughter) due to her Italian accent.
(Cue jokes about whether the 'straight' Brits could pass the nationality test or not)

Our hosts had banned discussions of Brexit at the start (too depressing), but, encouraged by some alcohol and good food, the topic turned this way. A number of the immigrants had gone either for settled status (65 pounds refunded) or full British passport

More maudlin Brexit observations. Last night I had a pleasure to be at a lovely dinner party in London, medics and scientists, mix from Columbian, Dutch, Sri Lankan/Dutch, Italian, American, and "straight" Brits like me.

Oligodendrocytes, a specific cell type found within the central nervous system, is responsible for generating the protective insulation. Several neurodegenerative diseases, such as multiple sclerosis and Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease involve the loss of the myelin sheath.
Brain cells, also known as neurons, rely on the myelin sheath, which insulates the axon and allows for info to travel at increased speed from the neuron to its target.
